<section xml:id="section-assignment3">
  <title>Assignment 3</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Explain how vector fields might be useful in each of the
        following situations. (6)
        <ol>
          <li>
            Planning a wind farm. 
          </li>
          <li>
            Shielding a solenoid.
          </li>
          <li>
            Tracking shoals of fish.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Draw these vector fields. (You can check this with a computer,
        but I want to see some of the calculations behind your
        drawing.) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            f(x,y) = (x^2 - y, y^2 -x)
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            f(x,y) = \left( \frac{1}{x+y}, \frac{1}{x-y} \right) 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            f(x,y) = (x \cos (\pi y), y \cos (\pi x))
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the integral curves for the following vector fields.
        (8) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            f(x,y) = \left( \frac{x}{2}, \frac{y}{4} \right) 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            f(x,y) = \left( \frac{1}{x^2}, \frac{1}{y^3} \right) 
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        What do integral curve mean for the following vector fields?
        (9) 
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            The vector field of ocean currents. (2D or 3D)
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            The vector field of gravitational force per unit mass
            around a gravitational source. (3D)
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            The vector field of temperature gradients over a
            landscape. (2D)
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove the follwoing operator composition identities for
        <m>f</m> a <m>C^2</m> scalar field on <m>\RR^3</m> and
        <m>F</m> a <m>C^2</m> vector field on <m>\RR^3</m>. (8) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \nabla \times (\nabla f) = (0,0,0)
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \nabla \cdot (\nabla \times F) = 0
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>F = (F_1,F_2,F_3)</m> is a <m>C^2</m> vector field on
        <m>\RR^3</m>, show that the property of being irrotational is
        <emph>not</emph> reserved if the components of <m>F</m> are
        re-arranged. (Use an example to show how the property is
        lost.) Why is the order of the components important? (4) 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the line ingrals. 
        <me>
          \int_\gamma F \cdot dr 
        </me>
        for these <m>F</m> and <m>\gamma</m>. (16) 
        <ol>
          <li><md>
            <mrow>
              \amp F(x,y) = (x^2 + y^2, x - y + 3) \amp \amp 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t+1,t-2) \amp \amp t \in [1,5[ 
            </mrow>
          </md></li>
          <li><md>
            <mrow>
              \amp F(x,y) = (x, y)
              \amp \amp 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (3 \cos 2t, 3 \sin t) \amp \amp t \in
              [0, \pi] 
            </mrow>
          </md></li>
          <li><md>
            <mrow>
              \amp F(x,y) = (-4x, -4y) 
              \amp \amp 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t \cos t, t \sin t) \amp \amp t \in
              [0, 2\pi] 
            </mrow>
          </md></li>
          <li><md>
            <mrow>
              \amp F(x,y) = \left(0, \frac{-1}{x} \right) \amp \amp 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t^2, t^3) \amp \amp t \in [0, 8]
            </mrow>
          </md></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>\gamma</m> be any path from <m>(0,0,0)</m> to
        <m>(9,9,9)</m> in <m>\RR^3</m> and consider this line
        integral. (8) 
        <me>
          \int_\gamma F \cdot dr
        </me>
        For which of the following vector fields is the line integral
        independent of path and why? When it is independent, what is
        the potential function?
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            F(x,y,z) = (2xyz^2, 2x^2z^2, 2x^2yz) 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            F(x,y,z) = (2xy^2z, 2x^2yz, x^2y^2z) 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            F(x,y,z) = (x^2y^2z, x^2yz^2, x^2y^2z^2) 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            F(x,y,z) = (xyz^2, x^2z^2, 2x^2yz) 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            F(x,y,z) = (2xyz^2, x^2z^2, 2x^2yz)
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>\gamma_a</m> be a family of path which are always
        perpendicular to a vector field <m>F</m> in <m>\RR^3</m>. (6)
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Why does the line integral of <m>F</m> along any
            <m>\gamma_a</m> vanish? 
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            If <m>F</m> is conservative, then <m>F = \nabla f</m> for
            some potential <m>f</m>. What is the relationship of the
            potential <m>f</m> to the paths <m>\gamma_a</m>?
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            If <m>F</m> is conservative and depends only on the
            <m>y</m> coordinate, what can you say about the paths
            <m>\gamma_a</m> and the potential <m>f</m>?
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
